1
00:00:01,858 --> 00:00:06,858
http://hiqve.com/

2
00:00:06,882 --> 00:00:09,384
Keep your eyes steadily on the disc.

3
00:00:10,552 --> 00:00:12,095
But it's getting harder.

4
00:00:13,097 --> 00:00:15,848
Your eyes are so tired from staring.

5
00:00:17,101 --> 00:00:19,936
Your eyelids feel like lead.

6
00:00:20,729 --> 00:00:22,647
They want to close.

7
00:00:23,190 --> 00:00:26,109
Heavier. Heavier.

8
00:00:27,403 --> 00:00:29,737
You must close them

9
00:00:30,447 --> 00:00:31,614
now.

10
00:00:35,327 --> 00:00:36,953
Ladies and gentlemen,

11
00:00:37,037 --> 00:00:40,373
these three people are now
in a state of hypnosis.

12
00:00:40,958 --> 00:00:43,876
Suggestions I make will
be implicitly accepted

13
00:00:44,002 --> 00:00:46,212
regardless of their nonsensical character.

14
00:00:54,638 --> 00:00:55,805
Archie.

15
00:00:56,807 --> 00:00:59,809
Archie, when you wake,

16
00:00:59,893 --> 00:01:03,396
there will be a kitten in front of you.

17
00:01:03,522 --> 00:01:07,650
There is nothing more
frightening in this world than this creature.

18
00:01:08,193 --> 00:01:10,111
You want nothing to do with it.

19
00:01:16,201 --> 00:01:17,869
No!

20
00:01:17,953 --> 00:01:19,829
No, get... No kitties!

21
00:01:20,497 --> 00:01:21,914
It's only a kitten.

22
00:01:21,999 --> 00:01:23,332
Get the cat out of here!

23
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:26,002
Gonna kill us all! Get it out!

24
00:01:33,927 --> 00:01:36,179
They come from Siberia,

25
00:01:36,305 --> 00:01:39,390
a fierce and dangerous place.

26
00:01:39,475 --> 00:01:41,476
Their mother, when she was with child,

27
00:01:41,560 --> 00:01:44,020
was attacked by a bear.

28
00:01:44,104 --> 00:01:46,272
The girls, even in their mother's womb,

29
00:01:46,356 --> 00:01:50,151
instinctively knew that to survive
they should cling to one another.

30
00:01:50,235 --> 00:01:52,528
They held on so tight,

31
00:01:52,613 --> 00:01:55,615
and this was the result.

32
00:01:55,699 --> 00:01:57,950
The birth was so excruciating,

33
00:01:58,035 --> 00:02:00,077
it killed their mother.

34
00:02:00,204 --> 00:02:03,539
Their father died of shock upon seeing them.

35
00:02:03,624 --> 00:02:07,168
Zoya and Nika were alone.

36
00:02:07,252 --> 00:02:09,295
But they proved in the womb

37
00:02:09,379 --> 00:02:12,006
their incredible survival ability.

38
00:02:12,090 --> 00:02:14,550
They lived off the milk of a goat

39
00:02:14,635 --> 00:02:17,094
and fallen acorns from a tree.

40
00:02:17,179 --> 00:02:21,557
They watched the wolves
and by the age of four could hunt.

41
00:02:21,642 --> 00:02:25,269
They taught themselves to speak, to sing,

42
00:02:25,354 --> 00:02:29,649
and even to play instruments
that they carved themselves.

43
00:02:51,797 --> 00:02:53,881
That's quite a story.

44
00:02:53,966 --> 00:02:55,883
I've recounted it 1,000 times

45
00:02:55,968 --> 00:02:58,010
and I still find it inspiring.

46
00:02:58,095 --> 00:03:01,556
How would you know
that they clung to each other in the womb?

47
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:03,307
You telling me my business, mister?

48
00:03:03,392 --> 00:03:07,353
No, no, no. I meant no disrespect.
I'm a doctor. I'm a natural skeptic.

49
00:03:07,479 --> 00:03:10,022
John Thackery. Knickerbocker Hospital.

50
00:03:10,107 --> 00:03:11,691
Lester Brockhurst.

51
00:03:11,775 --> 00:03:15,945
Mr. Brockhurst, would you be willing
to allow me to examine the girls?

52
00:03:16,071 --> 00:03:17,113
What for?

53
00:03:17,197 --> 00:03:20,491
Purely from a scientific perspective.

54
00:03:20,784 --> 00:03:22,577
When was the last time they saw a doctor?

55
00:03:22,661 --> 00:03:25,079
I got a physician's book.
I make sure they're healthy.

56
00:03:25,163 --> 00:03:28,708
No, of course.
And it looks like you're doing a fine job.

57
00:03:28,792 --> 00:03:31,419
One of them got dysentery last year.
I fixed her up.

58
00:03:31,837 --> 00:03:33,504
That's very impressive.

59
00:03:34,256 --> 00:03:36,924
So they don't share a digestive tract.

60
00:03:38,927 --> 00:03:40,845
It's not that I don't trust doctors,

61
00:03:40,929 --> 00:03:43,556
it's the time it takes.
That's money out of my pocket.

62
00:03:45,350 --> 00:03:49,478
So, what would you say
if I offered to hire them for a private show?

63
00:03:50,731 --> 00:03:52,398
We'll need transportation

64
00:03:52,482 --> 00:03:55,651
and a meal afterwards for me
at a reputable place.

65
00:03:56,153 --> 00:03:59,280
That can definitely be arranged.

66
00:03:59,364 --> 00:04:00,990
I'll be in touch.

67
00:04:34,858 --> 00:04:36,359
Morphine for the pain.

68
00:04:37,569 --> 00:04:41,656
The nurse will take you to another
room to rest for a couple of hours.

69
00:04:41,740 --> 00:04:44,951
The X-rays will have been developed by then.

70
00:04:45,035 --> 00:04:47,703
I'll come in and check on you
and take you home.

71
00:05:02,719 --> 00:05:04,053
Do those help?

72
00:05:04,846 --> 00:05:06,222
A little.

73
00:05:07,391 --> 00:05:11,227
The key seems to be in coating
the zinc needles with mercury.

74
00:05:11,311 --> 00:05:14,230
And the amount of current needed
for the zinc and mercury to ionize

75
00:05:14,314 --> 00:05:16,148
is dependent upon the size of the tumor.

76
00:05:16,233 --> 00:05:19,276
But if done correctly, the procedure claims
to kill all the malignant cells

77
00:05:19,361 --> 00:05:20,778
without disturbing the healthy tissue.

78
00:05:20,862 --> 00:05:23,656
It seems far less risky
than an all-out laryngectomy.

79
00:05:23,740 --> 00:05:26,325
I witnessed several of those in Paris.
They all failed.

80
00:05:26,410 --> 00:05:27,868
They couldn't reconstruct the windpipe

81
00:05:27,953 --> 00:05:30,538
after having removed
so much tissue with the tumor.

82
00:05:33,083 --> 00:05:34,542
I think it's worth trying.

83
00:05:35,794 --> 00:05:38,170
In the absence of any other solution, yes.

84
00:05:38,255 --> 00:05:40,673
But it's still experimental
and Zinberg would never...

85
00:05:40,757 --> 00:05:44,510
I don't have the luxury
of two years' worth of study.

86
00:05:44,594 --> 00:05:46,429
So I was hoping you'd help me.

87
00:05:47,597 --> 00:05:50,016
You have experience working in secret.

88
00:05:51,685 --> 00:05:53,436
I'm sorry.

89
00:05:53,729 --> 00:05:56,272
I just meant I need someone I can trust.

90
00:05:56,982 --> 00:05:59,692
Harold. Harold. Just tell Croker

91
00:05:59,776 --> 00:06:02,737
he'll have the last 100,000 by Tuesday.

92
00:06:04,072 --> 00:06:05,031
Right.

93
00:06:05,115 --> 00:06:08,868
And listen, Harold.
Where are we with the Brooklyn lines?

94
00:06:08,952 --> 00:06:12,747
'Cause I don't want to open the paper
and find they've all been auctioned off.

95
00:06:15,709 --> 00:06:16,709
Uh-huh.

96
00:06:17,961 --> 00:06:19,754
Right.

97
00:06:20,422 --> 00:06:21,422
That's fine.

98
00:06:21,506 --> 00:06:24,341
Just keep me apprised of the situation.

99
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:26,802
All right, I have to go, Prettyman.

100
00:06:26,887 --> 00:06:28,387
Goodbye.

101
00:06:30,640 --> 00:06:32,892
Nurse Elkins.

102
00:06:33,393 --> 00:06:34,643
What are you...

103
00:06:37,522 --> 00:06:39,440
I've been watching some of the other girls

104
00:06:39,524 --> 00:06:42,651
receive invitations
to the fundraising ball from their suitors.

105
00:06:45,197 --> 00:06:47,406
I was wondering when I was gonna get mine.

106
00:06:51,161 --> 00:06:54,830
How many other girls do I have to watch smile

107
00:06:54,915 --> 00:06:58,334
holding an invitation before I get one?

108
00:06:59,628 --> 00:07:00,961
I...

109
00:07:03,090 --> 00:07:05,841
Usually you have so many
clever things to say.

110
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:09,178
What's the matter?

111
00:07:10,847 --> 00:07:12,598
People can see.

112
00:07:12,682 --> 00:07:14,266
The glass.

113
00:07:14,351 --> 00:07:17,186
Doesn't bother me. Does it bother you?

114
00:07:20,482 --> 00:07:23,109
Maybe I should stop
so you can gather your thoughts.

115
00:07:23,193 --> 00:07:24,610
No.

116
00:07:26,071 --> 00:07:29,907
Well, then, my invitation?

117
00:07:31,368 --> 00:07:33,077
Soon.

118
00:07:33,161 --> 00:07:34,662
Very soon.

119
00:07:38,834 --> 00:07:40,501
Good.

120
00:07:47,551 --> 00:07:49,677
And this is the big top

121
00:07:50,887 --> 00:07:52,763
at the center of our circus.

122
00:07:54,558 --> 00:07:56,559
How full does your gallery get?

123
00:07:56,726 --> 00:07:59,019
When Thackery was leading the operations,

124
00:07:59,104 --> 00:08:01,564
standing room only.

125
00:08:01,648 --> 00:08:05,526
Not what yours is, is it, Russell?

126
00:08:07,404 --> 00:08:11,365
Well, we don't have the suction machine

127
00:08:11,449 --> 00:08:13,951
or any of the other electric gadgets.

128
00:08:14,035 --> 00:08:15,744
- Lighting is better in here, too.
- Mmm-hmm.

129
00:08:17,747 --> 00:08:21,333
I'm sure yours will still suffice.

130
00:08:21,418 --> 00:08:23,169
For what?

131
00:08:28,175 --> 00:08:31,010
Carr needs surgery.

132
00:08:31,511 --> 00:08:32,636
Umbilical hernia.

133
00:08:32,721 --> 00:08:36,974
Had it for years,
but I need to have it taken care of.

134
00:08:37,392 --> 00:08:39,268
I've read your hernia paper.

135
00:08:39,477 --> 00:08:41,103
I thought I'd do it for him.

136
00:08:41,188 --> 00:08:42,646
My procedure?

137
00:08:42,731 --> 00:08:45,441
Russell says he's read the paper thoroughly.

138
00:08:46,151 --> 00:08:47,818
But he's never performed it.

139
00:08:49,070 --> 00:08:50,529
And you'd be doing this at your place?

140
00:08:50,614 --> 00:08:52,072
Of course he would.

141
00:08:52,157 --> 00:08:54,575
We couldn't do it here.

142
00:08:57,704 --> 00:08:59,705
There are rules.

143
00:09:03,168 --> 00:09:04,668
I was thinking,

144
00:09:05,879 --> 00:09:07,796
and no disrespect to you, Russell,

145
00:09:07,881 --> 00:09:09,340
but since I did invent the procedure,

146
00:09:09,424 --> 00:09:11,967
perhaps I should be the one to perform it.

147
00:09:15,138 --> 00:09:16,805
Of course.

148
00:09:17,098 --> 00:09:18,641
You were the first choice.

149
00:09:22,938 --> 00:09:25,022
We should do it here

150
00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:27,524
if we can.

151
00:09:27,609 --> 00:09:29,485
I'll ask Thackery.

152
00:09:29,569 --> 00:09:31,737
See if he can square it with the board.

153
00:09:32,614 --> 00:09:34,490
Then we'll wait to hear from you.

154
00:09:38,912 --> 00:09:41,330
- Hello?
- We're in here.

155
00:09:43,750 --> 00:09:45,292
Sorry I'm late.

156
00:09:45,377 --> 00:09:47,044
It's quite all right. We waited to eat.

157
00:09:47,337 --> 00:09:48,963
Good evening, Dr. Gallinger.

158
00:09:50,715 --> 00:09:52,383
What are you doing here?

159
00:09:52,509 --> 00:09:55,636
Your wife graciously
invited me to dinner.

160
00:09:56,888 --> 00:09:59,515
Why would you invite
Dr. Cotton into our home?

161
00:10:00,016 --> 00:10:02,351
To thank him for what he did for me.

162
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:03,894
For us.

163
00:10:03,979 --> 00:10:06,188
He's the reason I feel the way I do.

164
00:10:06,481 --> 00:10:09,608
I am very pleased with
how Eleanor's been doing.

165
00:10:09,693 --> 00:10:11,110
I was just saying before you walked in,

166
00:10:11,194 --> 00:10:13,487
I think she might be
mentally fit to have children again.

167
00:10:14,364 --> 00:10:16,365
Isn't that wonderful, darling?

168
00:10:19,452 --> 00:10:21,036
The hospital's been doing so well,

169
00:10:21,121 --> 00:10:23,580
the state of New Jersey
has asked us to expand.

170
00:10:23,665 --> 00:10:25,374
We've seen patients from across the country,

171
00:10:25,458 --> 00:10:27,459
several from as far away as Europe.

172
00:10:27,544 --> 00:10:30,629
Lucky for you that
preying on the desperate is so lucrative.

173
00:10:30,714 --> 00:10:33,299
Everett, I will not have
you insult our guest.

174
00:10:33,425 --> 00:10:34,883
That's all right, Eleanor.

175
00:10:34,968 --> 00:10:36,719
A man's entitled to his opinion,

176
00:10:36,803 --> 00:10:38,637
misinformed as it may be.

177
00:10:38,722 --> 00:10:40,055
Misinformed?

178
00:10:41,558 --> 00:10:43,517
You mutilated my wife.

179
00:10:44,477 --> 00:10:47,396
And yet here you sit with your wife,

180
00:10:47,480 --> 00:10:50,482
a wonderful host
who's prepared this delicious meal.

181
00:10:50,567 --> 00:10:52,735
Six months ago, you dreamed
of an evening like this.

182
00:10:52,819 --> 00:10:54,903
You think so? Then you're misinformed.

183
00:10:57,574 --> 00:10:59,408
Excuse me.

184
00:10:59,617 --> 00:11:02,077
Um, let me give you an example.

185
00:11:02,287 --> 00:11:05,998
We had one young man, suffered terribly
his entire life from paranoia.

186
00:11:06,082 --> 00:11:08,542
Distrust of others. He heard voices.

187
00:11:08,668 --> 00:11:11,545
He was a hypochondriac
to the point where he couldn't function

188
00:11:11,629 --> 00:11:13,797
due to his own preoccupation with himself.

189
00:11:14,299 --> 00:11:17,509
Now, as with Eleanor,
I knew sepsis was the cause,

190
00:11:17,594 --> 00:11:19,303
so I removed his teeth at once.

191
00:11:20,305 --> 00:11:22,306
There was little change at first,

192
00:11:22,390 --> 00:11:25,142
but I owed it to this young man to help.

193
00:11:25,226 --> 00:11:27,061
And so I removed his tonsils
and his gallbladder.

194
00:11:27,145 --> 00:11:29,772
Now the distrust disappeared.

195
00:11:30,732 --> 00:11:32,608
So I kept on.

196
00:11:32,734 --> 00:11:35,819
In the end, his spleen,
colon, and testicles, they all came out.

197
00:11:36,321 --> 00:11:37,988
Dear God.

198
00:11:39,908 --> 00:11:42,201
I realize it may seem extreme,

199
00:11:42,285 --> 00:11:46,497
but I'm happy to report
the young man is now home,

200
00:11:46,623 --> 00:11:49,917
he's found employment,
no longer struggles with his symptoms.

201
00:11:50,001 --> 00:11:51,877
He is leading a relatively normal life.

202
00:11:51,961 --> 00:11:54,046
And five years ago,
that would have been impossible.

203
00:11:54,130 --> 00:11:55,839
Normal life?

204
00:11:56,132 --> 00:11:58,675
That young man isn't
a hypochondriac anymore

205
00:11:58,760 --> 00:12:01,845
'cause there's nothing left of him
to be hypochondriacal about.

206
00:12:01,930 --> 00:12:04,098
I don't understand why a doctor

207
00:12:04,182 --> 00:12:06,683
would shrink so timidly
from the frontiers of science.

208
00:12:06,768 --> 00:12:08,894
Is that so?

209
00:12:08,978 --> 00:12:10,229
Are you all right?

210
00:12:11,689 --> 00:12:13,148
I'm not feeling well.

211
00:12:13,983 --> 00:12:15,567
Where is your lavatory?

212
00:12:15,652 --> 00:12:19,613
Please, it's just up the
stairs and to the left.

213
00:12:30,583 --> 00:12:32,751
You really don't need to be so rude.

214
00:12:32,836 --> 00:12:34,086
He's our guest.

215
00:12:34,170 --> 00:12:36,130
Why did you invite him into our home?

216
00:12:37,006 --> 00:12:39,925
- I could kill him.
- Perhaps you could just remove his teeth.

217
00:12:42,512 --> 00:12:44,012
Without anesthetic.

218
00:12:44,889 --> 00:12:46,515
I wanted him here.

219
00:12:47,142 --> 00:12:50,894
And you will both please
try to remain civil throughout dessert.

220
00:12:52,605 --> 00:12:54,648
I don't have an appetite.

221
00:13:16,421 --> 00:13:18,672
I'm sorry, Mrs. Gallinger.

222
00:13:18,756 --> 00:13:20,966
I am going to head on home.
I'm not feeling well.

223
00:13:21,050 --> 00:13:24,094
I'm so sorry to hear that.

224
00:13:24,179 --> 00:13:26,221
But I'm very glad that you came

225
00:13:26,306 --> 00:13:30,267
so that I could show you my appreciation
for what you did for me.

226
00:13:30,351 --> 00:13:31,810
Of course.

227
00:13:31,895 --> 00:13:33,395
Good night.

228
00:13:53,124 --> 00:13:54,333
Are you ready?

229
00:14:03,301 --> 00:14:04,801
I'll do my best, Mother.

230
00:14:09,516 --> 00:14:11,475
I love you, my darling.

231
00:14:12,435 --> 00:14:14,686
I'll see you when you wake up.

232
00:14:31,246 --> 00:14:32,746
Do you need a drape?

233
00:14:34,207 --> 00:14:37,918
No, she's a patient. She needs a surgeon.

234
00:14:38,002 --> 00:14:39,002
I'm a surgeon.

235
00:14:54,852 --> 00:14:56,103
Thank you.

236
00:15:23,047 --> 00:15:25,591
Right, hand me the electrodes.

237
00:15:27,010 --> 00:15:29,261
Make sure and contact the zinc and mercury

238
00:15:29,345 --> 00:15:31,096
that's been injected into the tumor

239
00:15:31,180 --> 00:15:33,432
in order to ensure that
ionization is complete

240
00:15:33,516 --> 00:15:35,976
and the cancer cells are killed.

241
00:15:37,812 --> 00:15:39,438
You did a nice job with these.

242
00:15:40,607 --> 00:15:44,276
When this is over, I'm gonna have these
melted down into a necklace for her

243
00:15:44,360 --> 00:15:45,736
to cover the scar.

244
00:15:46,696 --> 00:15:48,280
1,000 milliamperes.

245
00:15:57,790 --> 00:16:01,251
Three, two, one.

246
00:16:22,273 --> 00:16:23,565
All right.

247
00:16:25,943 --> 00:16:27,444
Any change?

248
00:16:28,279 --> 00:16:30,030
It should shrink and soften.

249
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:37,079
We'll have to go again.
Increase the milliamperes to 1,200.

250
00:16:38,206 --> 00:16:39,414
What's going on?

251
00:16:40,208 --> 00:16:42,584
It's all right. I'm a surgeon here.
Dr. Chickering.

252
00:16:42,669 --> 00:16:45,837
There's no surgery scheduled for tonight
and no emergencies.

253
00:16:45,922 --> 00:16:47,255
You're not supposed to be in here.

254
00:16:47,423 --> 00:16:48,757
Yes, I am!

255
00:16:50,635 --> 00:16:51,843
And what about him?

256
00:16:55,264 --> 00:16:56,723
I'm harder to explain.

257
00:16:58,309 --> 00:17:00,936
- Excuse me.
- It's all right. It's all right.

258
00:17:01,396 --> 00:17:03,105
You're against the clock now.

259
00:17:05,566 --> 00:17:06,775
What are you doing?

260
00:17:06,859 --> 00:17:08,151
The laryngectomy.

261
00:17:08,945 --> 00:17:10,862
The tumor is braided into her larynx,

262
00:17:10,947 --> 00:17:13,782
trachea, and esophagus.
How do you expect to remove it?

263
00:17:13,866 --> 00:17:15,283
What do you suggest, then?

264
00:17:16,411 --> 00:17:20,288
Close her up and take a day
to consider your options.

265
00:17:20,373 --> 00:17:22,124
Options?

266
00:17:22,208 --> 00:17:25,127
We know what's gonna happen.
She starves to death or asphyxiates

267
00:17:25,211 --> 00:17:26,962
or chokes on her own spit.

268
00:17:34,679 --> 00:17:35,887
That part of the tumor may come away,

269
00:17:35,972 --> 00:17:37,764
but it'll take too much
of the posterior mucosa.

270
00:17:37,849 --> 00:17:40,434
I'll shave it as closely as I can,
try to limit the damage.

271
00:17:40,518 --> 00:17:42,519
She's tumorous through and through.

272
00:17:42,937 --> 00:17:44,855
God damn it,
there's no windpipe to work with.

273
00:17:44,939 --> 00:17:46,481
It's all tumor. It's torn to bits.

274
00:17:46,566 --> 00:17:48,525
Holes everywhere. Her lips are blue.

275
00:17:48,609 --> 00:17:51,069
She's hypoxic.

276
00:17:51,154 --> 00:17:53,321
Dr. Chickering,
what in God's name are you doing?

277
00:17:53,406 --> 00:17:55,073
In God's name I'm trying to save my mother!

278
00:17:55,158 --> 00:17:57,242
I take full responsibility.

279
00:17:57,326 --> 00:17:59,453
And if you worked here,
that might be worth a damn.

280
00:17:59,537 --> 00:18:03,123
There's no repairing that ventricle.
Just use the tissue to shore up that hole.

281
00:18:03,207 --> 00:18:04,916
Her breathing is becoming labored.

282
00:18:05,001 --> 00:18:06,209
What is Dr. Edwards doing here?

283
00:18:06,294 --> 00:18:07,586
He knew the procedure we were trying.

284
00:18:07,670 --> 00:18:09,045
Then why isn't he leading the surgery?

285
00:18:09,130 --> 00:18:10,297
I've lost sight in my left eye.

286
00:18:10,381 --> 00:18:12,716
It's only recently begun to improve a bit.

287
00:18:12,800 --> 00:18:16,094
So your assisting surgeon is half blind

288
00:18:16,179 --> 00:18:18,263
with no depth perception. Wonderful.

289
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:21,683
If you would kindly excoriate us later,
we are in trouble here.

290
00:18:25,730 --> 00:18:27,189
Oh, my.

291
00:18:28,941 --> 00:18:31,777
Harvest some tissue
from below the thyroid cartilage

292
00:18:31,861 --> 00:18:34,446
and use that to patch the space
on the tracheal rings.

293
00:18:34,530 --> 00:18:35,947
Can you see well enough to patch that space?

294
00:18:36,032 --> 00:18:37,115
Yes.

295
00:18:37,200 --> 00:18:40,702
Good. Now draw the tissue across.

296
00:18:41,829 --> 00:18:44,039
Don't worry yourself
with the cancerous section.

297
00:18:44,123 --> 00:18:46,500
You're just trying
to give her something to breathe through.

298
00:18:46,584 --> 00:18:49,669
Now hold it up against the anterior wall.

299
00:18:49,754 --> 00:18:50,962
I'll suture it.

300
00:18:53,007 --> 00:18:55,717
I'm not clean, but the instrument is.

301
00:18:56,260 --> 00:18:58,053
My patch is almost in.

302
00:18:59,180 --> 00:19:01,515
- She's still not getting any air.
- It's falling apart.

303
00:19:01,599 --> 00:19:03,767
It's shredding
the edge of the tumor near the subglottis.

304
00:19:03,851 --> 00:19:05,060
We need more tissue.

305
00:19:06,562 --> 00:19:07,896
She's cyanotic.

306
00:19:12,485 --> 00:19:14,611
There's no pulse.

307
00:19:14,695 --> 00:19:16,488
We can harvest from the soft palate

308
00:19:16,572 --> 00:19:19,491
and use it to cover
the shredded area near the subglottis.

309
00:19:21,536 --> 00:19:23,245
- Bertie.
- No.

310
00:19:25,164 --> 00:19:26,540
Let her go.

311
00:19:26,666 --> 00:19:28,333
She's been through enough.

312
00:19:29,252 --> 00:19:31,086
Let her go.

313
00:19:42,181 --> 00:19:43,890
Fuck.

314
00:19:45,351 --> 00:19:47,269
You're right,
it could never have succeeded.

315
00:19:47,353 --> 00:19:49,688
From the day she was diagnosed,
she was dead.

316
00:19:49,981 --> 00:19:53,650
It needed to be studied,
it needed to be perfected.

317
00:19:54,235 --> 00:19:55,735
But she was my mother.

318
00:19:56,571 --> 00:19:57,946
What was I supposed to do?

319
00:19:59,198 --> 00:20:01,449
I'm not running a circus.

320
00:20:01,534 --> 00:20:03,076
There are no high-wire acts here.

321
00:20:03,160 --> 00:20:04,828
But sometimes there needs to be.

322
00:20:04,912 --> 00:20:06,872
Sometimes risks have to be taken.

323
00:20:06,956 --> 00:20:09,291
Not in my operating rooms.

324
00:20:20,011 --> 00:20:21,803
I think it best if I resign.

325
00:20:26,726 --> 00:20:28,184
I agree.

326
00:20:30,062 --> 00:20:33,982
It'll save me the task of having to fire you
for violating protocols.

327
00:20:38,779 --> 00:20:40,405
Now go be with your family.

328
00:21:15,650 --> 00:21:17,192
I'm sorry.

329
00:21:20,696 --> 00:21:22,656
So am I.

330
00:21:28,996 --> 00:21:31,915
I was stupid to think I could do it.

331
00:21:31,999 --> 00:21:34,584
You must be furious with me.

332
00:21:35,503 --> 00:21:37,879
You had the courage to try.

333
00:21:38,381 --> 00:21:39,839
I couldn't even look.

334
00:23:06,844 --> 00:23:08,720
Why's Vera leaving?

335
00:23:08,804 --> 00:23:10,680
- I don't know.
- Pregnant.

336
00:23:10,765 --> 00:23:13,141
- She have any place?
- No.

337
00:23:13,309 --> 00:23:14,809
And the father?

338
00:23:14,894 --> 00:23:17,228
Whaler she met at a saloon.

339
00:23:17,313 --> 00:23:19,564
He's somewhere
in the Atlantic for all she knows.

340
00:23:19,648 --> 00:23:21,775
They can't just throw her in the street.

341
00:23:23,444 --> 00:23:26,112
I should try and get her in
on the ward at the Knick.

342
00:23:26,197 --> 00:23:29,449
They'll certainly be eager to hear from you.

343
00:23:29,533 --> 00:23:32,077
I thought I had baby
troubles just last month.

344
00:23:32,161 --> 00:23:35,830
I told you girls
don't let the fella finish inside you.

345
00:23:35,915 --> 00:23:38,875
I didn't. And Vera said neither did she.

346
00:23:39,043 --> 00:23:43,338
But it ain't like the fella's gonna listen to
a lot of reason while he's in his state.

347
00:23:43,422 --> 00:23:45,673
He's paying to finish where he wants.

348
00:23:48,427 --> 00:23:50,428
You got another way to make a dollar?

349
00:23:50,513 --> 00:23:52,847
Rose, you were a midwife. Tell Nettie.

350
00:23:54,016 --> 00:23:56,851
A man pulling out is just
wishful thinking most times.

351
00:23:59,772 --> 00:24:03,358
But there are other ways
to stop a man getting you pregnant.

352
00:24:03,442 --> 00:24:04,943
What kind of other ways?

353
00:24:06,570 --> 00:24:08,571
We can talk about this
another time.

354
00:24:14,787 --> 00:24:17,539
Sleep is coming.

355
00:24:20,209 --> 00:24:21,501
Sleep.

356
00:24:28,300 --> 00:24:30,927
- Did it work?
- Appears so.

357
00:24:31,011 --> 00:24:32,220
Very good.

358
00:24:34,390 --> 00:24:35,890
What do you think?

359
00:24:35,975 --> 00:24:38,101
You're Merlin the wizard.

360
00:24:38,185 --> 00:24:39,978
I can't fathom how that works.

361
00:24:40,062 --> 00:24:42,313
Neither can I.

362
00:24:42,398 --> 00:24:46,317
Seems to reach a part of the brain
that isn't physical.

363
00:24:46,402 --> 00:24:48,653
If one could suggest to someone
who was hypnotized

364
00:24:48,737 --> 00:24:51,614
to do all sorts of humorous feats,

365
00:24:51,699 --> 00:24:54,492
then why not
use it for something more practical?

366
00:24:54,660 --> 00:24:57,120
Change people's perception.

367
00:24:57,204 --> 00:25:00,748
- Curb their addiction.
- I've heard crazier ideas.

368
00:25:00,833 --> 00:25:03,042
In this room, actually.

369
00:25:03,127 --> 00:25:05,795
What habits does your subject have?

370
00:25:10,176 --> 00:25:12,427
Simple, direct instructions.

371
00:25:20,811 --> 00:25:22,437
Mr. Cleary.

372
00:25:24,064 --> 00:25:25,440
When I blow on you,

373
00:25:25,524 --> 00:25:28,109
you will wake and you will no longer

374
00:25:28,194 --> 00:25:30,486
be interested in smoking your pipe.

375
00:25:32,823 --> 00:25:34,282
You will detest it.

376
00:25:36,660 --> 00:25:38,953
The sight of it will anger you.

377
00:25:49,131 --> 00:25:50,590
The fuck is that?

378
00:25:50,674 --> 00:25:52,717
- It's your pipe.
- No. No.

379
00:25:52,801 --> 00:25:54,135
- That ain't mine.
- Yes, it is.

380
00:25:54,220 --> 00:25:56,179
- No.
- Do you want it?

381
00:25:56,263 --> 00:25:59,891
You bet your ass I do.

382
00:25:59,975 --> 00:26:02,227
I'm sorry, Doc, but all that hocus-pocus...

383
00:26:02,311 --> 00:26:05,480
Yeah, thanks for wasting our time.
Go on, get out.

384
00:26:08,609 --> 00:26:11,819
I wanted to present something to you.

385
00:26:12,696 --> 00:26:14,656
Are you familiar with Garrison Carr?

386
00:26:14,782 --> 00:26:16,074
No.

387
00:26:16,158 --> 00:26:18,201
He's a bit of an established thinker
in certain communities.

388
00:26:18,285 --> 00:26:21,120
He's in need of a hernia repair
and I'd like to perform it.

389
00:26:21,330 --> 00:26:23,081
Which communities?

390
00:26:23,165 --> 00:26:24,958
Little Africa.

391
00:26:25,042 --> 00:26:26,918
Harlem.

392
00:26:27,127 --> 00:26:30,964
Perhaps if the request to the board
came from you.

393
00:26:33,467 --> 00:26:35,093
I can try.

394
00:26:36,178 --> 00:26:38,137
It'll be good if there's a doctor in the room

395
00:26:38,222 --> 00:26:43,559
so I can revive them once they discover
your proposed patient is a Negro.

396
00:26:55,072 --> 00:26:56,948
Bertie the departed.

397
00:26:57,032 --> 00:26:58,741
I want to come back.

398
00:27:00,077 --> 00:27:01,911
What about Zinberg?

399
00:27:01,996 --> 00:27:03,204
He's extraordinary

400
00:27:03,289 --> 00:27:05,540
and what he's doing over there
would impress you.

401
00:27:07,543 --> 00:27:09,669
Turns out I'm a bit too reckless for him.

402
00:27:11,380 --> 00:27:14,966
I saw the notice in the paper
about your mother. I'm sorry.

403
00:27:18,470 --> 00:27:20,513
I need the speed of this place.

404
00:27:21,765 --> 00:27:23,099
Of you.

405
00:27:24,393 --> 00:27:25,977
Maybe I've changed.

406
00:27:27,229 --> 00:27:30,732
Perhaps I'm not as reckless
and fast as you remember.

407
00:27:32,234 --> 00:27:35,862
Algernon told me that last month you
performed surgery with a telephone.

408
00:27:38,907 --> 00:27:41,743
Some things have changed, I promise you.

409
00:27:42,619 --> 00:27:45,204
They have with me, too,
or else I wouldn't be here.

410
00:27:46,749 --> 00:27:48,958
I know now that this is where I belong.

411
00:27:51,211 --> 00:27:53,087
I've always known that.

412
00:28:02,181 --> 00:28:04,182
What's he saying?

413
00:28:04,350 --> 00:28:06,017
He doesn't like you being here.

414
00:28:06,101 --> 00:28:09,771
I'm just trying to help him
and get some information.

415
00:28:09,855 --> 00:28:11,564
How long has he been like this?

416
00:28:21,367 --> 00:28:23,743
Has he seen anyone
from the health department?

417
00:28:30,918 --> 00:28:33,544
- He's afraid you're trying to deport him.
- Assure him I'm not.

418
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:41,886
He's saying that the guy from the health
department threatened to.

419
00:28:41,970 --> 00:28:43,971
Was his name Speight?

420
00:28:44,056 --> 00:28:45,765
Do you know? Speight?

421
00:28:50,187 --> 00:28:52,397
He's saying he was a pig.

422
00:28:52,481 --> 00:28:54,982
- Fat like a barrel.
- Speight.

423
00:28:55,901 --> 00:28:59,779
Did you give this to Inspector Speight?

424
00:29:11,542 --> 00:29:13,584
This belonged to his brother Aldo.

425
00:29:13,669 --> 00:29:15,420
May I speak to him?

426
00:29:15,504 --> 00:29:17,422
Aldo died, signorina.

427
00:29:18,507 --> 00:29:20,341
Did he have the same symptoms?

428
00:29:33,397 --> 00:29:35,440
Yes, same symptoms.

429
00:29:35,524 --> 00:29:38,151
Fingers turned black, blood everywhere.

430
00:29:38,235 --> 00:29:42,113
He's saying that he came down the ship
feeling no well and in a week he died.

431
00:29:44,116 --> 00:29:47,034
Did your brother have money?
Was he well-off?

432
00:29:49,496 --> 00:29:50,496
No.

433
00:29:51,165 --> 00:29:54,208
Then how could he afford
a second-class ticket?

434
00:30:07,055 --> 00:30:08,639
He doesn't know.

435
00:30:08,765 --> 00:30:10,475
He doesn't know, but look,

436
00:30:10,559 --> 00:30:12,560
maybe Aldo stole it.

437
00:30:12,644 --> 00:30:15,104
But Gino came here honestly.
He's a good man.

438
00:30:15,189 --> 00:30:17,815
He has a family, a job, you know?
He didn't do no wrong.

439
00:30:23,155 --> 00:30:24,405
You must leave, I'm sorry.

440
00:30:24,490 --> 00:30:27,241
- He needs to see a doctor.
- He wants you to leave. I'm sorry.

441
00:30:27,326 --> 00:30:28,868
Of course. I'm sorry.

442
00:30:47,596 --> 00:30:50,264
After the swelling goes down, try to...

443
00:30:50,349 --> 00:30:52,600
Keep it elevated and then you can go home.

444
00:30:52,684 --> 00:30:54,352
Excuse me one moment.

445
00:30:59,274 --> 00:31:00,858
Lucy.

446
00:31:03,445 --> 00:31:06,447
I'm sorry.
I'm sure that must have been a surprise.

447
00:31:06,532 --> 00:31:08,282
A pleasant one.

448
00:31:08,367 --> 00:31:10,785
Welcome back.

449
00:31:11,286 --> 00:31:13,746
I know I felt more than you at one point,

450
00:31:13,830 --> 00:31:15,581
but I won't pretend my treatment towards you

451
00:31:15,666 --> 00:31:18,167
after our falling out
wasn't intended to hurt you.

452
00:31:18,252 --> 00:31:19,710
It did.

453
00:31:19,795 --> 00:31:21,337
Well, I was angry.

454
00:31:23,257 --> 00:31:25,049
And I acted like a child.

455
00:31:26,260 --> 00:31:27,802
And I'm sorry.

456
00:31:29,638 --> 00:31:32,181
I didn't expect you to forgive me.

457
00:31:32,266 --> 00:31:34,183
Well, I have.

458
00:31:34,268 --> 00:31:35,893
I've learned a lot about forgiveness.

459
00:31:35,978 --> 00:31:38,896
And though I don't expect it,
I hope you'll give me yours.

460
00:31:39,731 --> 00:31:41,148
Of course.

461
00:31:42,317 --> 00:31:44,485
I'd give anything to be friends again.

462
00:31:45,737 --> 00:31:47,196
Me, too.

463
00:31:48,198 --> 00:31:49,407
There's a ball coming up.

464
00:31:50,867 --> 00:31:52,159
Excuse me?

465
00:31:52,244 --> 00:31:54,120
To raise money for the new hospital.

466
00:31:55,747 --> 00:31:58,040
I heard you have a new lady friend.

467
00:31:58,667 --> 00:31:59,667
Oh.

468
00:31:59,918 --> 00:32:03,921
I just thought that if you wanted to attend,
it would only be fair to her...

469
00:32:04,673 --> 00:32:05,965
I don't know her name.

470
00:32:06,049 --> 00:32:07,258
Genevieve.

471
00:32:08,427 --> 00:32:10,386
To give her ample warning
so that she has time

472
00:32:10,470 --> 00:32:12,096
to get a dress and prepare.

473
00:32:13,932 --> 00:32:15,016
Thank you.

474
00:32:15,892 --> 00:32:17,184
Are you going?

475
00:32:18,687 --> 00:32:19,937
We'll see.

476
00:32:25,944 --> 00:32:27,862
Algie's gonna have Thackery ask the board

477
00:32:27,946 --> 00:32:32,658
if he can perform a surgery
on that D.W. Garrison Carr fellow.

478
00:32:34,244 --> 00:32:36,537
That Carr's in our boy's ear.

479
00:32:37,456 --> 00:32:40,583
Algie's got my vote, but he's pushing harder

480
00:32:40,667 --> 00:32:42,877
than the rest of the board can stand.

481
00:32:43,920 --> 00:32:46,130
Carr does more harm than good.

482
00:32:47,007 --> 00:32:48,382
Good afternoon.

483
00:32:49,801 --> 00:32:50,968
Let me have a Glenlivet.

484
00:32:51,053 --> 00:32:52,553
- Two, please.
- Yes, sir.

485
00:32:53,180 --> 00:32:54,388
It's too soon.

486
00:32:56,099 --> 00:32:58,559
Barrow said he's received inquiries
from nervous donors

487
00:32:58,644 --> 00:33:00,728
about Algie's involvement going forward.

488
00:33:01,396 --> 00:33:03,356
It's just one surgery.

489
00:33:03,440 --> 00:33:05,816
And Algie invented it, for God's sake.

490
00:33:05,901 --> 00:33:08,861
I'm not quibbling about our boy's skill.

491
00:33:09,154 --> 00:33:11,280
I would take him over Thackery these days.

492
00:33:11,365 --> 00:33:13,866
But our donors believe Thack is a god

493
00:33:13,950 --> 00:33:16,869
and we need them to continue believing that.

494
00:33:23,168 --> 00:33:24,669
It's not just...

495
00:33:24,753 --> 00:33:26,796
It's not just their estimation

496
00:33:26,880 --> 00:33:29,173
of Thackery that matters.

497
00:33:29,424 --> 00:33:32,927
They clearly don't want
the new Knick integrated.

498
00:33:33,011 --> 00:33:35,680
Meaning having a Negro doctor
or his Negro patients?

499
00:33:35,764 --> 00:33:37,515
Both.

500
00:33:37,599 --> 00:33:40,601
If we want Algie to move uptown with us,

501
00:33:40,686 --> 00:33:42,436
we have to sacrifice something.

502
00:33:46,274 --> 00:33:47,733
So the patients.

503
00:34:03,625 --> 00:34:06,043
So the barge takes all the
lower-class passengers

504
00:34:06,128 --> 00:34:08,379
over to Ellis Island for the full inspection,

505
00:34:08,463 --> 00:34:11,132
but a doc gives them a quick once-over here.

506
00:34:11,216 --> 00:34:13,050
What happens if they get marked?

507
00:34:13,135 --> 00:34:15,386
Well, then they got to see
another doctor on Ellis

508
00:34:15,470 --> 00:34:16,762
for a more thorough exam.

509
00:34:16,847 --> 00:34:18,556
If the doc thinks they're too sick

510
00:34:18,640 --> 00:34:20,057
and can't get cured easy here,

511
00:34:20,142 --> 00:34:21,642
then they can't come into the country.

512
00:34:21,727 --> 00:34:23,936
Over 25,000 last year alone.

513
00:34:24,146 --> 00:34:25,604
Where did they all go?

514
00:34:26,982 --> 00:34:28,774
Back to where they came from.

515
00:34:28,859 --> 00:34:31,026
What would send them back?

516
00:34:31,111 --> 00:34:33,362
Anything highly contagious.

517
00:34:33,447 --> 00:34:35,740
Trachoma, typhus, cholera...

518
00:34:35,824 --> 00:34:37,575
- Plague?
- Yeah.

519
00:34:37,659 --> 00:34:40,828
And they'd have
to go back to their country of origin?

520
00:34:40,912 --> 00:34:42,288
Not with embarkation.

521
00:34:42,372 --> 00:34:44,707
See, the shipping companies
have to pay a $100 fine

522
00:34:44,791 --> 00:34:46,417
